06:07.980 --> 06:13.240
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and fantasy.

06:15.900 --> 06:17.580
And here are your hosts.

06:21.840 --> 06:23.620
This is Daryl Lane. And Bill Vernon.

06:24.000 --> 06:29.720
1953 marked the publication of a little-known science fiction classic. Charles Harness's short novel entitled The Rose.

06:30.060 --> 06:33.240
And we have to say little known because of the curious history of the book.

06:33.500 --> 06:38.540
Right. First of all, Harness attempted to sell a book in the United States markets, but the editors were unwilling to buy it.

06:38.980 --> 06:43.020
He then had to sell it in England to a relatively obscure magazine, Authentic Science Fiction.

06:44.020 --> 06:50.640
My agent at the time, Forest Akerman of, I think, Los Angeles, paddled it around here and there.

06:51.000 --> 07:00.380
Nobody in this country would buy it. It went to John Camel, and he wrote a nice two-line letter bug. He just couldn't use it.

07:00.820 --> 07:10.240
It wasn't the kind of thing that any science fiction magazine or fantasy and science fiction magazine was publishing at the time.

07:10.240 --> 07:15.820
And I should have known better for writing it. But I wanted to write it, so I did.

07:17.660 --> 07:25.500
And finally, Akerman sold it to this little authentic magazine in England, and they published it.

07:26.140 --> 07:29.720
Authentic was under the editorship of H.J. Campbell when The Rose was published.

07:30.200 --> 07:35.780
Publication of The Rose is considered to be the capstone achievement in the generally mediocre 85 issue run of the magazine.

07:35.780 --> 07:40.920
It would have languished in the pages of Authentic were it not for the fact that the British critics absolutely loved it.

07:41.320 --> 07:45.320
Arthur Clark, Judith Merrill, Brian Aldis, and in particular Michael Morkock praised it.

07:45.680 --> 07:51.680
It was through the almost single-handed efforts of Morkock that The Rose was published in book form, again in England, some years later.

07:52.840 --> 07:55.840
Arthur Clark saw it, got the Morkock for it.

07:56.380 --> 08:08.580
And Morkock, who was getting them through the editableness over there at that time, asked to have his people, Compact Books, publish it.

08:09.540 --> 08:13.460
And we haven't had a contract for it, and they did publish it.

08:14.180 --> 08:21.260
Then it was picked up fairly quickly by two other British outfits in hardcover form.

08:22.500 --> 08:28.920
And of course they had to pad it out with the two other stories to make it in a book size.

08:29.760 --> 08:36.260
The two short stories added to pad the length of the volume in which The Rose was finally published are The New Reality and The Chess Players.

08:36.540 --> 08:42.820
The New Reality, written in 1950 and first published in Thrilling Wonder Stories, is considered to be Harness Finest short story.

08:42.820 --> 08:48.560
The Chess Players is a clever little story based on the trouble it develops when a chess club encounters a chess-playing rat.

08:48.820 --> 08:53.040
In fact, many of Harness's works allude to chess. We ask him if he enjoys the game.

09:15.500 --> 09:21.140
It wasn't until 1969 that The Rose was made available in the United States, thanks to the efforts of Damon Knight.

09:21.580 --> 09:24.480
Berkeley published it then, and so far that has been the only American edition.

09:53.540 --> 10:02.800
It struck us that one reason The Rose could not find a United States publisher in 1953 was that American readers simply were not ready for a book heavy on the metaphysical rather than the hardware.

10:03.320 --> 10:04.740
We ask Harness if he might agree.

10:12.820 --> 10:18.300
Everybody was guided pretty much by the Dean of Science Fiction, John Camel, and he was a hardware man.

10:19.780 --> 10:24.500
And everything had to obey the laws of physics or it would be unacceptable.

10:25.480 --> 10:27.180
More about The Rose on our next show.

10:33.360 --> 10:42.500
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, a production of the Permian Basin Science Fiction Association produced in conjunction with Odessa College in Odessa, Texas.

11:22.960 --> 11:25.520
The Rose on our next show.

11:27.180 --> 11:29.580
Stay with us.

11:57.180 --> 11:59.020
This is Bill Vernon and Daryl Lane.

11:59.260 --> 12:03.880
On our last show we talked with science fiction author Charles Harness about his classic short novel, The Rose.

12:04.480 --> 12:13.720
We learned how The Rose was enthusiastically embraced by the British critics, yet it wasn't published in the United States until 16 years had elapsed from its initial publication in an obscure British magazine.

12:13.920 --> 12:16.560
In this show we'll look at some of the literary aspects of The Rose.

12:17.100 --> 12:20.980
Many of Harness's earlier works were written hastily, but we hasten to add not clumsily.

12:21.420 --> 12:24.320
The Rose, on the other hand, required a considerable length of time for completion.

12:25.200 --> 12:28.920
That was one of the stories where I didn't know how it was going to come out.

12:29.980 --> 12:35.100
And in fact, I worked on that one for two years, Bill. This is not a two-month slide.

12:37.320 --> 12:44.000
I read all the books on the arts in the Stanford Public Library. This is one year.

12:44.000 --> 12:50.140
I took notes on them for an entire two-week vacation one year.

12:51.400 --> 12:54.360
And then it gradually began to come together.

12:55.800 --> 13:07.840
And I used, of course, as you've seen in the story, Oscar Wilde's story of the Nightingale and the Rose, which I'd read many years before and I was quite impressed by it.

13:08.500 --> 13:11.940
Harness also filled us in on some other details about the writing of the Rose.

13:12.260 --> 13:16.200
For instance, its early incarnations were longer and it originally had another name.

13:17.280 --> 13:19.980
Let me give you a little bit more history on this.

13:22.060 --> 13:30.220
There was a time when the Rose was in a longer form and it had the name not the Rose, but invitation.

13:31.620 --> 13:45.760
It was an intergalactic thing where the Earth was being examined to see whether it would be admitted into a galactic relevant.

13:47.480 --> 13:50.700
And it didn't have the ending that it now has.

13:51.680 --> 13:57.180
Damon Knight liked that, but he couldn't get his publishers to accept it.

13:57.780 --> 14:07.680
This again was a year or so before it came out and it's in authentic and it's short form.

14:10.740 --> 14:16.600
So at that point I said, maybe I'm going to shorten this thing down, give it a different ending.

14:18.120 --> 14:19.320
So I did.

14:19.760 --> 14:24.980
I cut it from 45,000 words down to, I think it's about 30,000.

14:28.360 --> 14:34.900
And it's Ackerman, Dan was able to spell it, he's authentic in England.

14:36.020 --> 14:38.140
The central theme of the Rose is difficult to capsule.

14:38.640 --> 14:42.480
It's a love story involving two central characters, Rui Jacques and Anne of Antal.

14:43.140 --> 14:46.160
It's set in the midst of a future confrontation between science and art.

14:46.580 --> 14:49.120
And it describes a transcendental evolution of man into Superman.

14:49.120 --> 14:56.180
Harness and his brother Billy, who as we should learn in a later show, died when Harness was still in high school, were the models for the central characters.

14:57.480 --> 15:02.560
Rui Jacques again resembles my brother a great deal.

15:06.740 --> 15:23.600
And if you can visualize that guy with his sarcasm, his biting wit, his contempt for all, all the, well, I don't know.

15:23.600 --> 15:35.040
But he was a, he had a high personal integrity and a impatience with convention and so on.

15:36.560 --> 15:38.840
At least in his head he did.

15:40.460 --> 15:43.740
And I wanted to get him into print.

15:45.440 --> 15:52.480
And of course Anne of Antal is me, although I had to take on a female form to make it effective.

15:53.780 --> 16:04.160
I would have, at one time I would have been pleased to die if it would bring him back, but of course that would just be the story.

16:05.980 --> 16:10.720
But it was a thought and it was a psychic force driving the story.

16:11.500 --> 16:15.620
Do yourself a favor, find a copy of the rose in your local used bookstore and read it.

