In 1968, Berkeley published Charles Harness' novel, The Ring of Ritternell, his first work to appear in 15 years.

17:55.580 --> 17:59.580
It's the story of two brothers, one a lawyer, the other a poet, in a far distant future.

18:00.260 --> 18:04.260
He or Harness, who is himself a lawyer, tells us about the very personal inspiration for the poet.

18:05.220 --> 18:10.420
My brother Billy was several years older than I, in fact he was nine years older than I.

18:11.340 --> 18:16.880
And he died when I was just about to graduate from high school.

18:17.120 --> 18:22.080
He had tumors of the brain, which in those days were inoperable.

18:22.300 --> 18:29.440
Today they don't, it wouldn't be too much trouble to operate if they couldn't do it then.

18:30.420 --> 18:36.100
So I have remembered him and I have never let him go.

18:37.500 --> 18:43.780
And he has done in several of my stories The Ring of Ritternell.

18:44.260 --> 18:53.380
He was the brother who was destroyed by the chief bad guy, but his brain was retained.

18:53.920 --> 18:54.880
He was the poet.

18:55.760 --> 18:57.880
His name was Omer.

18:58.840 --> 19:02.560
In 1977, Wolfhead, Harness' fourth novel came out.

19:02.840 --> 19:04.180
It was his first novel in nine years.

19:04.460 --> 19:10.520
Wolfhead describes a post-atomic holocaust America and the struggle between various cultures that populate the desolate land.

19:10.980 --> 19:15.880
Harness told us that when he wrote Wolfhead, he went against the conventional wisdom that one shouldn't write about certain subjects.

19:16.800 --> 19:23.420
I started out writing it. I thought I would do a thing which is ground upon.

19:23.420 --> 19:27.320
You're not supposed to write post-atomic novels.

19:29.240 --> 19:30.980
It's really unacceptable.

19:32.360 --> 19:34.300
But here seem to be a good one.

19:35.460 --> 19:40.720
A real life character, Richard Nixon, inspired Harness' characterization of the malevolent leader of the underworld.

19:41.460 --> 19:46.240
Well, I thought, see, here's this guy. He's about to take over the country.

19:46.920 --> 19:50.440
Anything he does is okay just because he says so.

19:50.440 --> 19:55.240
And I'm going to have a character like that in Wolfhead.

19:57.800 --> 20:02.380
So I put him in there. He was the president of the underworld.

20:03.480 --> 20:08.180
And he would come out and rule the upper world, except he didn't.

20:09.040 --> 20:11.760
Even the wolf of the title was inspired by a real life dog.

20:12.580 --> 20:21.600
The wolf was modeled at the time on an Alaskan Husky dog that lived next door to us.

20:22.900 --> 20:27.240
And she and I were great friends, so I thought I'd put her in it.

20:28.100 --> 20:31.640
When Harness reminisced about Wolfhead, he told us he was pretty much pleased by it.

20:32.160 --> 20:36.700
It's one of my happier efforts. It's not really serious.

20:38.100 --> 20:43.940
Well, some of it is. You know, at one time it had a different ending.

20:45.000 --> 20:47.200
Of course, we had to ask Harness about that different ending.

20:47.620 --> 20:50.560
Keep in mind that during his writing career, he was a full-time patent attorney.

20:51.240 --> 20:55.640
The answer to this question provides an interesting insight into other ways the real world can intrude into fiction.

20:56.560 --> 20:59.520
And I have to cough when I think about it. Excuse me while I cough.

21:05.320 --> 21:08.080
This is a psychological cough.

21:11.280 --> 21:16.060
In the original ending, the girl lived.

21:17.380 --> 21:25.440
But I got involved in some chemical litigation that I lost.

21:27.380 --> 21:32.700
And I was so angry and so disappointed, I said, somebody has to die.

21:33.660 --> 21:41.440
So I killed the heroine and wrote some poetry for her benefit so she wouldn't feel too badly about it.

21:42.140 --> 21:45.560
And that's the poetry, of course, is in the front and in the back.

21:47.660 --> 21:50.480
So that's a little sidelight on that.

21:50.980 --> 21:53.380
We'll have more with Charles Harness on our next show.

