23:27.540 --> 23:31.400
Science fiction author Charles Harness began writing in earnest again in the late 70s,

23:31.620 --> 23:33.420
and he produced three novels in short order.

23:33.940 --> 23:36.880
The Catalyst is the story of a patent lawyer who works for a chemical company.

23:37.280 --> 23:40.160
In this respect, it resembles some short stories Harness wrote a decade earlier,

23:40.480 --> 23:42.500
the Alchemist and an ornament to his profession.

23:42.500 --> 23:47.880
The Catalyst actually started out as a longer mainstream novel, but Harness, unable to sell it,

23:47.980 --> 23:49.460
fixed it up as a science fiction work.

23:49.860 --> 23:51.680
His brother figured heavily in this book, too.

24:12.500 --> 24:12.980
This is a story of a man who was in the first department.

24:16.080 --> 24:22.960
And one of the stories there involved a peculiar whistle,

24:23.680 --> 24:31.540
which was derived from cheap, may safely graze by Johann Sebastian Bach.

24:32.660 --> 24:35.960
But that long version never sold, and I thought,

24:35.960 --> 24:37.720
well, I'm not going to let it die.

24:38.260 --> 24:43.140
I will convert it to a science fiction work with all the proper trappings

24:44.300 --> 24:48.580
and things you need to call it science fiction, which I did.

24:49.620 --> 24:53.980
In 1981, Harness published a novel that was sort of a throwback to his early period,

24:54.220 --> 24:55.440
Galaxy Galloping Days.

24:56.320 --> 25:00.480
Firebird is made up of early Harness devices, such as a time loop and the rebirth of the cosmos.

25:00.800 --> 25:03.580
Here, Harness tells us about the basis for the story in Firebird.

25:04.500 --> 25:07.760
I'm sure you recognize the basic story here.

25:08.220 --> 25:10.060
This is Tristan and his shoulder.

25:11.820 --> 25:16.100
I don't know whether you go in for Wagner or not,

25:16.420 --> 25:23.740
but it is his shoulder and Tristan drinking what she thinks is the poison drink,

25:24.600 --> 25:29.240
but it's his lovely lecture again, and they fall in love.

25:29.240 --> 25:36.660
And after that, just about everything parallels the Tristan and his shoulder story

25:36.660 --> 25:45.940
as you would find it in Wagner's opera, including Death of the Man and the Flight.

25:46.900 --> 25:50.620
Editor David Hartwell of Pocket Books also influenced Harness's approach to this novel.

25:50.620 --> 25:58.280
In the beginning, when I first wrote David Hartwell of Pocket Books,

25:59.740 --> 26:04.080
I should mention he is a medieval scholar.

26:04.280 --> 26:08.060
This is what he got his PhD in English in.

26:09.000 --> 26:13.580
And he was quite familiar with the Tristan legend from there,

26:14.560 --> 26:22.380
and he found Welsh origins for it, and he had me change the names to look like Welsh names.

26:23.740 --> 26:27.860
And he said, make him more of a Renaissance knight,

26:28.420 --> 26:31.160
and I put in some chaff, which is easy enough.

26:32.900 --> 26:35.380
So, there's something that looked like a chaff thing.

26:36.220 --> 26:38.780
I worked it into the plot, and it came out okay.

26:40.660 --> 26:43.800
But it is a never-content, no-for-nothing contribution.

27:03.260 --> 27:06.860
Harness is retired from his lifelong profession of being a patent attorney.

27:06.860 --> 27:10.880
He's recently produced a couple of short stories in a novel, and more are in the works.

27:11.300 --> 27:15.320
He's a gentleman who, while working full-time, produced a small body of quality science fiction.

27:15.620 --> 27:17.180
We asked him how he wishes to be remembered.

27:18.180 --> 27:23.220
My request there is, please forget me, let me sink into oblivion,

27:24.040 --> 27:30.040
let the waves wash up over the sand, and everything disappears.

27:31.660 --> 27:32.540
Honest to God.

27:32.540 --> 27:35.780
We somehow doubt that Mr. Harness will be forgotten.

